body:
This is what I mean by renaming:

```
// File: bla.sol
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT

code

// File: Library.sol
// SPDX-License-Identifier: GNU GPLv3

code

```

If you use --license MIT, you're basically throwing away the GNU GPLv3 license for part of the code. I like to still keep this like this:

```
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT

// File: bla.sol
// License-Identifier: MIT

code

// File: Library.sol
// License-Identifier: GNU GPLv3

code

```

This way you can still see the license for each file, but there's also a proper SPDX-license for the whole thing, to keep all the tooling happy.

@boringcrypto the renaming requirement (and maybe even the removal of abi encoder) feel like they might be too much for hardhat core. The removal of licenses and the setting of a single license are pretty generic, so they seem fine to me, but maybe we should stop at that point. Any other thing you need can be accomplished simply by overriding a task:

```js
subtask(TASK_FLATTEN_GET_FLATTENED_SOURCE, async (hre, args, runSuper) => {
  const flattened = await runSuper()
  
  // do extra changes to flattened output

  return flattened
})
```

Sorry for being a PITA. I know that adding extra flags that do more stuff is easy and it seems like a thing you can do for free, but it increases the codebase (and therefore the complexity of the project, and the likelihood of bugs) and it makes it harder to document.
